## The 5 Pattern Rules

### Rule 1: One Concept = One Factory

**Always:** Expose exactly one factory function per adapter concept.

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Single factory with overloads
export function direct<S>(endpoint: string, options: {...}): Source<...>;
export function direct<T>(endpoint: string | function): Destination<T, T>;

// ❌ Bad: Multiple factories for one concept
export function directSource(endpoint: string, options: {...}): Source<...>;
export function directDestination(handler: function): Destination<T, T>;
```

**Why:** This is the cornerstone of our DX. Users think in concepts (direct, http, simple), not operations (source, destination).

### Rule 2: Always Use Directory Structure (Even Single-Interface)

**Always:** Use separate files for each operation, even for single-interface adapters.

```typescript
// ✅ Good: simple/source.ts + simple/index.ts
// source.ts
export class SimpleSourceAdapter<T> implements Source<T> {
  constructor(private producer: () => T | Promise<T>) {}
  subscribe(context, handler, abortController, onReady) { ... }
}

// index.ts
import { SimpleSourceAdapter } from './source';
export function simple<T>(producer): Source<T> {
  return new SimpleSourceAdapter<T>(producer);
}

// ❌ Bad: Everything in one file (simple.ts)
export class SimpleSourceAdapter<T> implements Source<T> { ... }
export function simple<T>(producer): Source<T> { ... }
```

**Why:** Consistency. Every adapter follows the same pattern, making the codebase predictable and easier to extend.

### Rule 3: Factories Return Interfaces, Not Classes

**Always:** Factory return types must be interface types (`Source<T>`, `Destination<T, R>`), never class types.

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Returns interface type
export function http<T, R>(options: HttpOptions): Destination<T, HttpResult<R>> {
  return new HttpDestinationAdapter<T, R>(options);
}

// ❌ Bad: Returns class type (exposes implementation)
export function http<T, R>(options: HttpOptions): HttpDestinationAdapter<T, R> {
  return new HttpDestinationAdapter<T, R>(options);
}
```

**Why:** Interface types provide encapsulation. Users don't depend on implementation details, making future refactoring easier.

### Rule 4: Use Structural Type Guards

**Always:** Use structural checks (`arguments.length`, `typeof`) to discriminate factory overloads.

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Structural checks
export function direct<...>(...): Source<...> | Destination<...> {
  if (arguments.length === 2) {
    return new DirectSourceAdapter(endpoint, options);
  }
  if (typeof endpoint === 'function') {
    return new DirectDestinationAdapter<T>(endpoint);
  }
  throw new Error('Invalid arguments');
}

// ❌ Bad: Value-based checks (runtime behavior dependency)
export function direct<...>(...): Source<...> | Destination<...> {
  if (options !== undefined) {
    return new DirectSourceAdapter(endpoint, options);
  }
  return new DirectDestinationAdapter<T>(endpoint);
}
```

**Why:** Structural checks are reliable and type-safe. Value-based checks can fail unexpectedly (e.g., `options = {}` vs `options = undefined`).

### Rule 5: Always Use Multi-Interface Naming

**Always:** Include the operation in class names, even for single-interface adapters.

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Operation in name
export class SimpleSourceAdapter<T> implements Source<T> { }
export class HttpDestinationAdapter<T, R> implements Destination<T, HttpResult<R>> { }
export class DirectSourceAdapter<T> implements Source<T> { }
export class DirectDestinationAdapter<T> implements Destination<T, T> { }

// ❌ Bad: Generic names (can't add operations later)
export class SimpleAdapter<T> implements Source<T> { }
export class HttpAdapter<T, R> implements Destination<T, HttpResult<R>> { }
```

**Why:** Future-proofing. If we need to add a destination to `simple`, we can add `SimpleDestinationAdapter` without renaming the existing class.

---

## Class Naming Convention

**Pattern:** `{Concept}{Operation}Adapter`

- **Concept:** The adapter name (Direct, Http, Simple, Timer, Log, etc.)
- **Operation:** The interface implemented (Source, Destination, Transform, etc.)
- **Suffix:** Always `Adapter`

**Examples:**
```typescript
// Source implementations
class SimpleSourceAdapter<T> implements Source<T> { }
class DirectSourceAdapter<T> implements Source<T> { }
class TimerSourceAdapter<T> implements Source<T> { }

// Destination implementations
class HttpDestinationAdapter<T, R> implements Destination<T, HttpResult<R>> { }
class DirectDestinationAdapter<T> implements Destination<T, T> { }
class LogDestinationAdapter<T> implements Destination<T, void> { }
```

